00:02:13.680 --> 00:02:20.000
The thing was that the Americans were incredibly afraid of German men.

14
00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:25.640
They thought if they had given them a tin of vegetables
they would have built a machine gun out of it.

15
00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:30.920
That’s why no German men were allowed into Tempelhof Airport.

16
00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:39.960
Each regiment in Berlin was tasked
with founding a youth club.

17
00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:44.520
One fine day

18
00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:49.440
they asked us if we would be willing
to unload coal...

19
00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:54.400
We all stood up as one.

20
00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:59.560
Around 900 to 1000 young people
from the 21 clubs.

21
00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:08.720
We were on duty for 24 hours

22
00:03:09.408 --> 00:03:13.880
and got one meal,
just like the one the Air Force got.

23
00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:18.120
Of course that was sensational for our families,
having one less mouth to feed.

24
00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:20.480
We were starving at the time.

25
00:03:21.168 --> 00:03:24.800
It was a big metal bowl with five indentations:

26
00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:26.080
For soup,

27
00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:28.600
potatoes, meat,

28
00:03:29.523 --> 00:03:31.600
custard.
Everything was in there.

29
00:03:32.461 --> 00:03:34.720
Everybody got to eat their fill.

30
00:03:35.182 --> 00:03:37.600
If necessary you got seconds.

31
00:03:38.378 --> 00:03:40.520
That was a dream come true.

32
00:03:42.829 --> 00:03:45.600
Everything was just about survival back then.

33
00:03:46.725 --> 00:03:48.000
My mother...

34
00:03:48.639 --> 00:03:50.680
My father died in Russia.

35
00:03:55.027 --> 00:03:57.200
My mother had three children

36
00:03:57.630 --> 00:03:59.640
and her mother to look after...

37
00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:03.880
She didn’t earn enough for us to be able to buy the food we needed.

38
00:04:04.523 --> 00:04:09.280
That’s why we appreciate how good we have it today...
apart from our health.

39
00:04:30.939 --> 00:04:32.320
That’s where the bags were.

40
00:04:32.908 --> 00:04:34.960
They were lifted out,
then brought to the door here

41
00:04:35.507 --> 00:04:36.920
and thrown out of the door.

42
00:04:37.087 --> 00:04:40.160
The truck almost reached the lower edge.

43
00:04:41.909 --> 00:04:44.840
And on the truck there were always six to eight boys.

44
00:04:48.895 --> 00:04:50.693
They took the bags

45
00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:54.440
and packed them towards the front
until the plane was empty.

46
00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:34.000
It seemed like a miracle to us

47
00:05:34.135 --> 00:05:36.040
that there were not more accidents.

48
00:05:36.409 --> 00:05:38.000
The way they were flying here

49
00:05:38.151 --> 00:05:42.360
and the way they were landing and taking off...
It was incredible.

50
00:05:43.578 --> 00:05:45.800
They were handling their machines so well:

51
00:05:46.879 --> 00:05:51.400
The plane came to a halt, the hatch opened, the guy fell down
and was already asleep.

52
00:05:52.045 --> 00:05:55.920
The Americans were so free and casual,
that was something we admired.

53
00:05:56.106 --> 00:06:00.120
We were still used to
someone bellowing orders at us.

54
00:06:00.801 --> 00:06:02.880
At school the teachers would still beat us.

55
00:06:28.672 --> 00:06:31.200
Reports about the airlift

56
00:06:31.882 --> 00:06:34.560
never talk about the fact

57
00:06:35.646 --> 00:06:39.720
that we unloaded the planes
in the first couple of months.

58
00:06:41.857 --> 00:06:45.680
I have never understood why we were never mentioned.

